<div id=3D"use-ipv4-sec2" class=3D"accordion-collapse collapse">
<div class=3D"accordion-body">
<p><strong>A step-by-step guide to use IPTP Networks=E2=80=99 IPv4 Subnet C=
alculator</strong></p>
<p>Choose the preferred Network class, which is determined by its first bit=
s, by clicking either three options:</p>
<ul>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"68133001301">Class A (8 bits), B (16 bits) and C =
(24 bits)</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"24789708501">Select the target Subnet from the dr=
opbox according to the Network class you chose</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"84936162101">Enter the IP address. An example IP =
address is already in place and can be used immediately</li>
</ul>
<p>Hit the Calculate button to view the result list of all the network and =
IP address values.</p>
<p>The necessary data IPv4 Subnet Calculator needs to calculate:</p>
<ul>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"45846959701"><strong>Network class:</strong>Netwo=
rk is divided into Class A, Class B and Class C. Class A network uses the f=
irst 8 bits of the IP address as its =E2=80=9Cnetwork part.=E2=80=9D, while=
 Class B uses the first 16 bits and Class C uses the first 24 bits</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"91982585101"><strong>Subnet:</strong>Subnet inclu=
des two parts: The subnet mask, followed by the CIDR notation</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"65076822701"><strong>IP address:</strong>IPv4 add=
ress uses a 32-bit address and can support 232 IP addresses. IPv4 has 4 gro=
ups of numbers =E2=80=93 called octets. Each octet ranges between 0 and 255=
 and is separated by dots (.)</li>
</ul></div>
<p></p></div>
