<div id=3D"ipv4-sec3" class=3D"accordion-item targetDiv">
<div class=3D"accordion-header"><button class=3D"accordion-button collapsed=
" type=3D"button" data-bs-toggle=3D"collapse" data-bs-target=3D"#results-ip=
v4-sec3" aria-expanded=3D"false" aria-controls=3D"results-ipv4-sec3" plerdy=
-tracking-id=3D"69373452201">Results</button></div>
<div id=3D"results-ipv4-sec3" class=3D"accordion-collapse collapse">
<div class=3D"accordion-body">
<p>IPv4 Subnet Calculator tool will use that information to calculate and d=
isplay comprehensive information about:</p>
<ul>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"87275818801"><strong>Network Address:</strong>The=
 first part of the subnet mask and is the same with the first part of the I=
P address.</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"80276651501"><strong>Broadcast Address:</strong>T=
he last address on the subnet. It is used to send data (broadcast) to every=
 host on that subnet.</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"90408979001"><strong>Total Number of Hosts:</stro=
ng>Total number of addresses available on the network.</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"30038756101"><strong>Usable Host IP Range:</stron=
g>It refers to the range of IP addresses that can be assigned to hosts. The=
 range starts with the address right after the network address and ends at =
one address before the broadcast address.</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"46200869901"><strong>Number of Usable Hosts:</str=
ong>The addresses that can be assigned to hosts. The total number of addres=
ses without the first address (the network address) and the last address (t=
he broadcast address).</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"76816453601"><strong>Wildcard Mask:</strong>Wildc=
ard masks refers to the inverted bits of the subnet mask to be used with ro=
uting protocols (OSPF) and access control lists (ACLs).</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"78853730601"><strong>Binary Subnet Mask:</strong>=
Subnet mask in binary format.</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"15166294401"><strong>IP Class:</strong>IP address=
es are categorized into five classes, ranging from Class A to E. Class D is=
 for multicasting and Class E is for future use.</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"88557706401"><strong>CIDR Notation:</strong>IP ad=
dress is written with a number of bits (CIDR number), with a forward-slash =
(/) in between.</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"36119487701"><strong>IP Type:</strong>Show whethe=
r the IP address is public (on the Internet) or private (local networks).</=
li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"31390876601"><strong>Binary ID:</strong>IP addres=
s in binary format, which consists of only 0s and 1s.</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"77726800001"><strong>Integer ID:</strong>IP addre=
ss in integer format, which consists of numbers from 0 =E2=80=93 9.</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"85983648001"><strong>Hex ID:</strong>IP address i=
n hexadecimal format, which starts with the =E2=80=9C0x=E2=80=9D, and consi=
sts of numbers from 0 =E2=80=93 9 and letters from A =E2=80=93 F.</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"67095272601"><strong>In-addr.arpa:</strong>A doma=
in name for reverse DNS lookup. It is the IP addresses in the reverse order=
. For example, when looking up the IP address of 27.78.101.154, the returne=
d result is 154.101.78.27.in-addr.arpa.</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"40989858801"><strong>IPv4 Mapped Address:</strong=
>IPv4 Mapped Address is used to present a 32-bit IPv4 address as a 128-bit =
IPv6 address. Its format starts with 80 =E2=80=9C0=E2=80=9D bits, followed =
by 16 bits set in 1s (=E2=80=9CFFFF=E2=80=9D in hexadecimal), and ends with=
 the original 32-bit IPv4 address written in hexadecimal format.</li>
<li plerdy-tracking-id=3D"52862429101"><strong>6to4 Prefix:</strong>6to4 is=
 an IPv4 to IPv6 migration scheme. 6to4 addresses always start with 2002, f=
ollowed by the original 32-bit IPv4 address written in hexadecimal format. =
IPv4 Subnet Calculator will also return the data about all the possible net=
works for that IP address (Network Address, Usable Host Range, Broadcast Ad=
dress).</li>
</ul></div>
